The limitations of strategic culture theory—such as its failure to reconcile inconsistencies and its reliance on abstract assumptions—mean that anything unexplained by realist frameworks is deemed irrational (fact 12). This contrasts with the Confucian model’s flexibility in applying beliefs (fact 3), where normative assumptions and goals still serve as prescriptive rules (fact 4), but psychological factors are labeled irrational (fact 5). While strategic culture circumvents investigating inconsistencies (fact 6), it also fails to refine metrics for rational choice (fact 7), leaving researchers to assess decisions inconsistent with realism by inferring beliefs from historical evidence (fact 9).  

